99,north,"**My Current Analysis of the Boulder-Pushing Problem**

Okay, here's what I'm seeing. I'm currently at coordinates (36, 11) on the map. My objective, as always, is to manipulate boulders onto the fountains. I need to take stock of the situation. There's a boulder right to my south at (36, 12). Let's see... I need to consider the layout. I see fountains at (43, 9) and (43, 11). Checking the boulder positions, I have boulders at (36, 12), (37, 13), (38, 13) and (39, 10). Let's get a clearer picture from the map representation:

```
#...<...{#  y=9
#...#`...#  y=10  (` is at 39,10)
#.@#####{#  y=11  (@ is at 36,11)
#.`##.{..#  y=12  (` is at 36,12)
#.``.....#  y=13  (` are at 37,13 and 38,13)
##.......#  y=14
```

Now let's start dissecting this. Pushing the boulder at (36, 12) south seems like an obvious first move, but I need to be careful about the walls. If I push it south, it will be at 36,13 and then at 36,14 but 36,14 is a wall (##). So, pushing south from 36,12 won't be possible. Pushing east from 36,12? No, I see walls at 37,12 and 38,12.

Okay, let's step back. I *can* push the boulder at (36, 12) south if the space below is open, which it is (. at 36,13). But then (36,13) I can push the boulder east, but I need to clear the way. There's another boulder at (37, 13) which is an obstacle.

It looks like the boulder at (39, 10) may be a good first target. It is currently east of my current location.

I am at (36, 11) and (39,10) is my current target. So, I will move north to 36,10, east to 38,10, and then start pushing the boulder at (39, 10) east.
So the first path would be:
north to 36,10,
east to 37,10, 38,10.
Push the boulder at 39,10 east. Let's do that.","message:
